# ML Code Standards

## Model Classes

- Inherit `BaseModel` from `src/models/base_model.py` — never break the interface
- `predict()` returns binary `pd.Series` (0/1)
- `predict_proba()` returns float `pd.Series` (scores)
- `save()` / `load()` use `joblib`
- No `print()` — use `logging`

## Hyperparameter Tuning (Optuna)

- New models must include an Optuna search space in `MLModel.optuna_objectives()`
- Do not hardcode default hyperparameters from docs without an Optuna search
- Log the search space and best trial parameters so the choice is reproducible
- Keep the selected defaults in config/code aligned with the Optuna best trial

## Type Hints

```python
def fit(self, X: pd.DataFrame, y: pd.Series) -> None: ...
def predict_proba(self, X: pd.DataFrame) -> pd.Series: ...
```

## No Hardcoded Paths

```python
# ❌
model = joblib.load("src/models/my_model.joblib")

# ✅ read from config
cfg = yaml.safe_load(open("params/ml_params.yaml"))
```

## Imbalance Handling

Always address the ~0.15% fraud rate explicitly:
- XGBoost: `scale_pos_weight=ratio`
- LightGBM: `is_unbalance=True`
- sklearn: `class_weight='balanced'` or `'balanced_subsample'`
- Never evaluate with accuracy — use ROC-AUC or PR-AUC
